05593nam a22007575i 9781487535032DE-B159720240306125748.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20192019onc    fo  d z      eng d  a97814875350327 a10.3138/97814875350322doi  a(DE-B1597)645219  a(OCoLC)1128823218  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  aonccCA-ON 7aPOL0540002bisacsh1 aSong, Jesook , eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aOn the Margins of Urban South Korea :bCore Location as Method and Praxis /cJesook Song, Laam Hae. 1aToronto : bUniversity of Toronto Press, c[2019] 4cÂ©2019  a1 online resource (208 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tEditors' Note -- tAbbreviations -- tIntroduction: Core Location, Asia as Method, and a Relational Understanding of Places -- t1 The Idea of Chinatown: Rethinking Cities from the Periphery -- t2 Seeing the Development of Jeju Global Education City from the Margins -- t3 Against the Construction State: Korean Pro-greenbelt Activism as Method -- t4 Marriage Migration as Spatio-Temporal Fix in Pohang's Post-Industrial Urban Development through Saemaul -- t5 "Locations of Reflexivity": South Korean Community Activism and Its Affective Promise for "Solidarity" -- t6 The Education Welfare Project at Pine Tree Hill: A Core Location to Assess Distributional and Transitional Forms of Justice -- t7 Situating the Space of Labour: Activism, Work, and Urban Regeneration -- tAfterword -- tContributors0 aOpen Accessuhttps://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_abf2funrestricted online access2star  aThis book provides a rich and illuminating account of the peripheries of urban, regional, and transnational development in South Korea. Engaging with the ideas of "core location," a term coined by Baik Young-seo, and "Asia as method," a concept with a century-old intellectual lineage in East Asia, each chapter in the volume discusses the ways in which a place can be studied in an increasingly globalized world. Examining cases set in the Jeju English Education City, anti-poverty and community activist sites, rural areas home to large numbers of migrant women, and Korea's Chinatowns, greenbelts, and textile factories, the collection develops a relational understanding of a place as a constellation of local and global forces and processes that interact and contradict in particular ways. Each chapter also explores multiple modes of urban marginality and discusses how understanding them shapes the methods of academic praxis for social justice causes and decolonialized scholarship. This book is the outcome of several years of interdisciplinary collaborations and dialogues among scholars based in geography, architecture, anthropology, and urban politics.  afunded by University of Toronto Libraries  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCommunity development, UrbanzKorea (South). 0aDecolonizationzKorea (South). 0aKnowledge, Sociology of. 0aSociology, UrbanzKorea (South). 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / World / Asian.2bisacsh  aAsia as method.  aCore Location.  aMarginality.  aPraxis.  aSouth Korea.  aUrban development.  aUrban social movement.1 aCho, Mun Young, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEom, Sujin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHae, Laam, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aHae, Laam, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJeong, Hyeseon, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOh, Youjeong, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPark